  "response_text": "A good post-workout meal for building muscle that costs less than $2 can be challenging, but it's definitely possible! Here are a few options that are both affordable and effective for muscle recovery:\n\n1. **Cottage Cheese and a Banana**: \n   - Cottage cheese is high in protein, and a small serving can often be found for around $1. A banana typically costs around $0.25. Together, they provide protein and carbohydrates for recovery.\n\n2. **Peanut Butter on Whole Wheat Bread**:\n   - One slice of whole wheat bread (around $0.20) with a tablespoon of peanut butter (approximately $0.30) provides a good mix of protein and healthy fats. \n\n3. **Eggs and Rice**:\n   - One boiled egg (about $0.15) and a half-cup of cooked rice (around $0.15) can be a great source of protein and carbs. You can often find bulk rice very cheaply.\n\n4. **Tuna Salad on Crackers**:\n   - A small can of tuna (about $1) combined with a few whole grain crackers (approximately $0.50) offers a good amount of protein and complex carbohydrates.\n\n5. **Oatmeal with Protein Powder**:\n   - A half-cup of oats (about $0.15) with a scoop of protein powder (if you buy in bulk, it can be around $0.50) creates a filling meal that's high in protein and carbs.\n\n6. **Greek Yogurt with Honey**:\n   - A small container of plain Greek yogurt (about $1) drizzled with a bit of honey (around $0.10) is rich in protein and adds some simple sugars for recovery.\n\nWhen preparing these meals, consider buying in bulk where possible to reduce costs further. Additionally, prices may vary depending on your location, so adjust accordingly!",
